# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hall-effect-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] A **Hall effect sensor** (also known as a **Hall sensor** or **Hall probe**) is any sensor based on the *Hall effect* (named after physicist Edwin Hall), in which a voltage is produced proportional to one axial component of the magnetic field vector **B**.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors are used for proximity sensing, positioning, speed detection, and current sensing applications and are common in industrial and consumer applications.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hundreds of millions of Hall sensor integrated circuits (ICs) are sold each year by about 50 manufacturers, with the global market being valued at around a billion dollars.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] In a Hall sensor, a fixed DC bias current is applied along one axis across a thin strip of metal called the Hall element transducer.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Sensing electrodes on opposite sides of the Hall element along *another* axis measure the difference in electric potential (voltage) across the axis of the electrodes.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The current's charge carriers are deflected by the Lorentz force in the presence of a magnetic field perpendicular to their flow.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The sensing electrodes measure the potential difference (the Hall voltage) proportional to the axial component of the magnetic field that is perpendicular to *both* the current's axis and the sensing electrodes' axis.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect sensors respond both to static magnetic fields and to changing ones.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The Hall voltage is also temperature-dependent and can have an offset.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Due to the proportionality of the Hall voltage to the charge carrier mobility and the concentration of the majority charge carriers, the Hall effect is an established method for determining these parameters in semiconductor technology.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect devices produce a very low signal level and thus require amplification.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The vacuum tube amplifier technology available in the first half of the 20th century was too large, expensive, and power-consuming for everyday Hall effect sensor applications, which were limited to laboratory instruments.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Even early generation transistor technology was unsuited; it was only with the development of the low-cost silicon chip-based integrated circuit (IC) micro-technology that the Hall effect sensor became suitable for mass application.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Devices sold as Hall sensors nowadays contain both the sensor as described above and a high gain IC amplifier in a single package.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] These Hall sensor ICs may add a stable voltage regulator in addition to the amplifier to allow operation over a wide range of supply voltage and boost the Hall voltage for a convenient analog signal output proportional to the magnetic field component.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] In some cases, the linear circuit may cancel the offset voltage of Hall sensors.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Moreover, AC modulation of the driving current may also reduce the influence of this offset voltage.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors are called *linear* if their output is proportional to the incident magnetic field strength.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This output signal can be an analog voltage, a pulse-width modulation (PWM) signal, or be communicated digitally over a modern bus protocol.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors may also be *ratiometric* if their sensitivity is also proportional to their supply voltage.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] With no magnetic field applied, their *quiescent output voltage* is typically half of the supply voltage.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] While the Hall element is an analog device, *Hall switch* ICs often additionally incorporate threshold detection circuitry to form an electronic switch which has two states (on and off) that output a binary digital signal.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Their outputs may be open collector NPN transistors (or open drain n-type MOSFETs) for compatibility with ICs that use different supply voltages.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Rather than a voltage being produced at the Hall sensor signal output wire, an output transistor is turned on, providing a circuit to ground through the signal output wire.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Schmitt trigger filtering may be applied (or integrated into the IC) to provide a clean digital output that is robust against sensor noise.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The hysteresis thresholds for switching (specified as BOP and BRP) categorize digital Hall ICs as either unipolar switches, omnipolar switches, or bipolar switches, which may sometimes be called latches.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Unipolar (e.g., A3144) refers to having switching thresholds in only one polarity of the magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Omnipolar switches have two sets of switching thresholds, for both positive and negative polarities, and so operate alternatively with a strong positive or a strong negative magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Bipolar switches have a positive BOP and a negative BRP (and thus require both positive and negative magnetic fields to operate).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The difference between BOP and BRP tends to be greater for bipolar switches described as latches, which remain in one state much longer (i.e. they latch onto their last value) and require a greater field strength to change states than bipolar switches require.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The naming distinction between "bipolar" and "latch" may be a little arbitrary, for instance, the datasheet for the Honeywell SS41F describes it as "bipolar", while another manufacturer describes their SS41F with comparable specifications as a "latch".
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall elements measure only the sensing axis component of the magnetic field vector.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Because that axial component may be positive or negative, some Hall sensors can sense the binary direction of the axial component in addition to its magnitude.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] An additional perpendicularly-oriented Hall element (e.g. in § Dual Hall sensor ICs) must be incorporated to determine a 2-D direction, and another perpendicularly-oriented Hall element must be added to detect the full 3-D components of the magnetic field vector.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Because Hall sensor ICs are solid-state devices, they are not prone to mechanical wear.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Thus, they can operate at much higher speeds than mechanical sensors, and their lifespan is not limited by mechanical failure (unlike potentiometers, electromechanical reed switches, relays, or other mechanical switches and sensors).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] However, Hall sensors can be prone to thermal drift due to changes in environmental conditions and to time drift over the lifetime of the sensor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect devices (when appropriately packaged) are immune to dust, dirt, mud, and water.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] These characteristics make Hall effect devices better for position sensing than alternative means such as optical and electromechanical sensing.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The bandwidth of practical Hall sensors is limited to the hundreds of kilohertz, with commercial silicon ones commonly limited to 10–100 kHz.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] As of 2016, the fastest Hall sensor available in the market has a bandwidth of 1 MHz but uses non-standard semiconductors.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Magnetic flux from the surroundings (such as other wires) may diminish or enhance the field the Hall probe intends to detect, rendering the results inaccurate.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors can detect stray magnetic fields easily, including that of Earth, so they work well as electronic compasses: but this also means that such stray fields can hinder accurate measurements of small magnetic fields.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] To solve this problem, Hall sensors are often integrated with magnetic shielding of some kind.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Mechanical positions within an electromagnetic system can instead be measured without the Hall effect using optical position encoders (e.g., absolute and incremental encoders) and induced voltage by moving the amount of metalcore inserted into a transformer.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] When Hall is compared to photo-sensitive methods, it is harder to get an absolute position with Hall.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] While a single Hall element is susceptible to external magnetic fields, a differential configuration of two Hall elements can cancel stray fields out from measurements, analogous to how common mode voltage signals are canceled using differential signaling.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect sensors may be used in various sensors such as rotating speed sensors (bicycle wheels, gear-teeth, automotive speedometers, electronic ignition systems), fluid flow sensors, current sensors, and pressure sensors.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors are commonly used to time the speed of wheels and shafts (see Figure 1), such as for internal combustion engine ignition timing, tachometers and anti-lock braking systems.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Common applications are often found where a robust and contactless alternative to a mechanical switch or potentiometer is required.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] These include: electric airsoft guns, triggers of electropneumatic paintball guns, go-kart speed controls, smartphones, and some global positioning systems.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] One of the most common industrial applications of Hall sensors used as binary switches is in position sensing (see Figure 2).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect sensors are used to detect whether a smartphone's cover (that includes a small magnet) is closed.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Some computer printers use Hall sensors to detect missing paper and open covers and some 3D printers use them to measure filament thickness.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors are used in some automotive fuel-level indicators by detecting the position of a floating element in the fuel tank.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors affixed to mechanical gauges that have magnetized indicator needles can translate the physical position or orientation of the mechanical indicator needle into an electrical signal that can be used by electronic indicators, controls, or communications devices.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect magnetometers (also called tesla meters or gauss meters) use a "Hall probe", with a Hall element, to measure magnetic fields or inspect materials (such as tubing or pipelines) using the principles of magnetic flux leakage.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] A Hall probe is a device that uses a calibrated Hall-effect sensor to directly measure the strength of a magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Since magnetic fields have a direction as well as a magnitude, the results from a Hall probe are dependent on the orientation, as well as the position, of the probe.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors may be utilized for contactless measurements of direct current in current transformers.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] In such a case the Hall sensor is mounted in a gap in the magnetic core around the current conductor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] As a result, the DC magnetic flux can be measured, and the DC in the conductor can be calculated.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] When electrons flow through a conductor, a magnetic field is produced.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Thus, it is possible to create a non-contacting current sensor or ammeters.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] A sensor voltage is applied across two terminals and the third provides a voltage proportional to the current being sensed.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This has several advantages; no additional resistance (a *shunt*, required for the most common current sensing method) needs to be inserted in the primary circuit.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Also, the voltage present on the line to be sensed is not transmitted to the sensor, which enhances the safety of measuring equipment.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This configuration also provides an improvement in signal-to-noise ratio and drift effects of over 20 times that of a bare Hall device.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The range of a given feedthrough sensor may also be extended upward and downward by appropriate wiring.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] To extend the range to lower currents, multiple turns of the current-carrying wire may be made through the opening, each turn adding to the sensor output the same quantity; when the sensor is installed onto a printed circuit board, the turns can be carried out by a staple on the board.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] To extend the range to higher currents, a current divider may be used.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The divider splits the current across two wires of differing widths and the thinner wire, carrying a smaller proportion of the total current, passes through the sensor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] A variation on the ring sensor uses a split sensor that is clamped onto the line enabling the device to be used in temporary test equipment.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] If used in a permanent installation, a split sensor allows the electric current to be tested without dismantling the existing circuit.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The output is proportional to both the applied magnetic field and the applied sensor voltage.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] If the magnetic field is applied by a solenoid, the sensor output is proportional to the product of the current through the solenoid and the sensor voltage.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] As most applications requiring computation are now performed by small digital computers, the remaining useful application is in power sensing, which combines current sensing with voltage sensing in a single Hall effect device.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] By sensing the current provided to a load, and using the device's applied voltage as a sensor voltage, it is possible to determine the power dissipated by a device, to implement a wattmeter.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall effect devices used in motion sensing and motion limit switches can offer enhanced reliability in extreme environments.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] As there are no moving parts involved within the sensor or magnet, typical life expectancy is improved compared to traditional electromechanical switches.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Additionally, the sensor and magnet may be encapsulated in an appropriate protective material.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Commonly used in distributors for ignition timing (and in some types of crank- and camshaft-position sensors for injection pulse timing, speed sensing, etc.) the Hall effect sensor is used as a direct replacement for the mechanical breaker points used in earlier automotive applications.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Its use as an ignition timing device in various distributor types is as follows: a stationary permanent magnet and semiconductor Hall effect chip are mounted next to each other separated by an air gap, forming the Hall effect sensor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] A metal rotor consisting of windows or tabs is mounted on a shaft and arranged so that, during shaft rotation, the windows or tabs pass through the air gap between the permanent magnet and semiconductor Hall chip.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This effectively shields and exposes the Hall chip to the permanent magnet's field respective of whether a tab or window is passing through the Hall sensor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] For ignition timing purposes, the metal rotor will have several equal-sized windows or tabs matching the number of engine cylinders (the #1 cylinder tab will always be unique, for discernment by the Engine Control Unit).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This produces a uniform output similar to a square wave, since the shielding and exposure time are equal.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This signal is used by the engine computer or ECU to control ignition timing.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The sensing of wheel rotation is especially useful in anti-lock braking systems.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The principles of such systems have been extended and refined to offer more than anti-skid functions, now providing extended vehicle-handling enhancements.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Some types of brushless DC electric motors use Hall effect sensors to detect the position of the rotor and feed that information to the motor controller.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This allows for more precise motor control.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors in 3 or 4-pin brushless DC motors sense the position of the rotor and facilitate switching the transistors in the right sequence.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] A Hall-effect thruster (HET) is a device that is used to propel some spacecraft, after the spacecraft gets into orbit or farther out into space.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] In the HET, atoms are ionized and accelerated by an electric field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] A radial magnetic field established by magnets on the thruster is used to trap electrons which then orbit and create an electric field due to the Hall effect.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] A large potential is established between the end of the thruster where neutral propellant is fed, and the part where electrons are produced; so, electrons trapped in the magnetic field cannot drop to the lower potential.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] They are thus extremely energetic, which means that they can ionize neutral atoms.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Neutral propellant is pumped into the chamber and is ionized by the trapped electrons.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Positive ions and electrons are then ejected from the thruster as a quasineutral plasma, creating thrust.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The thrust produced is extremely small, with a very low mass flow rate and a very high effective exhaust velocity/specific impulse.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This is achieved at the cost of very high electrical power requirements, on the order of tens of kW per Newton of thrust.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensor ICs often integrate digital electronics.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This enables advanced corrections to the sensor characteristics (e.g. temperature-coefficient corrections), digital communication to microprocessor systems, and may provide interfaces for input diagnostics, fault protection for transient conditions, and short/open-circuit detection.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Some Hall sensor ICs include DSP, which can allow for more processing techniques directly within the sensor package.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Some Hall sensor ICs integrate an analog-to-digital converter and an I2C (Inter-integrated circuit communication protocol) IC for direct connection to a microcontroller's I/O port.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The ESP32 microcontroller even has an integrated Hall sensor that hypothetically could be read by the microcontroller's internal analog-to-digital converter, though it does not work.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall sensors normally require at least three pins (for power, ground, and output).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] However, two-wire ICs only use a power and ground pin, and instead communicate data using different current levels.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Multiple two-wire ICs may operate from a single supply line, to further reduce wiring.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall-effect switches for computer keyboards were developed in the late 1960s by Everett A.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Due to high manufacturing costs these keyboards were often reserved for high-reliability applications such as in aerospace and the military.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] As mass-production costs have declined, an increasing number of consumer models have become available.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Hall-effect sensors can also be found on some high-performance gaming keyboards (made by companies such as SteelSeries, Wooting, Corsair), with the switches themselves containing magnets.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Applications for Hall effect sensing have also expanded to industrial applications, which now use Hall effect joysticks to control hydraulic valves, replacing the traditional mechanical levers with contactless sensing.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Such applications include mining trucks, backhoe loaders, cranes, diggers, scissor lifts, etc.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] This is useful for counting a series of increments (an incremental encoder) to make a linear or rotary encoder, whereby a moving or rotating arrangement of magnets produces an alternating magnetic pattern sensed as a quadrature encoded pattern.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] That pattern can then be decoded to provide both the speed and direction of movement or simply counted up and down to determine the position or angle.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] (When only one Hall element is used, the direction of linear or rotary encoders cannot be determined).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] The two elements placed at a precise distance apart from each other on the die may be oriented in the same direction, in which case the magnetic pole-to-pole pitch should ideally be two times the Hall element-to-element pitch.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/hall-effect-sensor] Alternatively, the Hall elements may be oriented at 90 degrees to provide sensing in two axes.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In magnetism and electromagnetism, **magnetic field** is a physical property of space that quantifies the magnetic influence at a given location.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic fields deflect moving electric charges (including electric currents), apply torques on magnets to twist them in the direction of the magnetic field, and attract or repel magnets and magnetic material such as iron.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In addition, a time-varying magnetic field induces electrical currents.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic fields are created by magnetic materials and by moving electric charges (including electrical current).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The latter is important in creating electromagnets: devices that precisely control magnetic fields by changing the current through the electromagnet.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic fields are used throughout modern science and technology.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In electrical engineering and electromechanics it is important in the design and use of electric motors, generators, transformers, electromagnets, and inductors among many other devices.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In material science, magnetic forces give information about the charge carriers in a material through the Hall effect in addition to other uses.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In geology and geophysics, Earth's magnetic field gives information about earth's interior while local magnetic field measurements are used in mineral exploration and other measurements.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Too, Earth's magnetic field creates a magnetosphere which shields the Earth's ozone layer and the rest of the planet from the solar wind.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In physics the relationship between the magnetic and electric fields forms the field of electrodynamics which is important to understand a wide range of phenomena including light (also known as electromagnetic radiation) and the properties of antenna and transmission lines.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Since both strength and direction of a magnetic field may vary with location, it is described mathematically by assigning a vector to each point of space, making it a vector field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] There are two different, but closely related, vector fields which are called "magnetic field".
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] While the best names for these fields is the subject of long running debate, the underlying physics is uncontested.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The international ISO 80000-6 standard defines **magnetic field** as "that component of an electromagnetic field which is characterized by the magnetic field strength vector **H** and the magnetic flux density vector **B**." This standard also defines **B** and **H** as given in the sections below.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] While there is wide agreement on these definitions of **B** and **H**, there are many alternative names for both (see sidebars in the corresponding sections).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Also known as **magnetic flux density**, the magnetic **B** field causes magnetic forces, magnetic torques and electromagnetic induction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Therefore, it can be defined by any equation that describes these phenomena.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Here **F** is the force on the particle, *q* is the particle's electric charge, **E** is the external electric field, **v**, is the particle's velocity, and × denotes the cross product.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For more details see Lorentz Force or the § Magnetic force on a charged particle section below.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The SI unit of **B** is tesla (symbol: T).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The Gaussian-cgs unit of **B** is the gauss (symbol: G).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] (The conversion is 1 T ≘ 10000 G.) One nanotesla corresponds to 1 gamma (symbol: γ).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] While **B** creates magnetic forces and torques on objects and induces currents in conducting wires, it is not always easy to calculate.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where $\mu _{0}$ is the vacuum permeability, and **M** is the magnetization vector which represents how magnetized a given region of material is and is defined below.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In a vacuum, **B** = μ0**H** making them equivalent to each other.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Defined this way, **H** can in many circumstance be treated as if it is only due to electrical currents with corrections accounting for **H** due to nearby magnetic material.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In any case, **B** still needs to be calculated from **H** if forces, torques, induced currents, or energy changes need to be calculated.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The SI unit of **H** is the ampere per metre (A/m) and the Gaussian unit is the oersted (Oe).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Instruments used to measure the local magnetic **B**-field are known as a magnetometers.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Important classes of magnetometers include induction magnetometers (or search-coil magnetometers) which measure only varying magnetic fields, rotating coil magnetometers, Hall effect magnetometers, NMR magnetometers, SQUID magnetometers, and fluxgate magnetometers.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic fields of distant astronomical objects are measured through their effects on local charged particles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For instance, electrons spiraling around a field line produce synchrotron radiation that is detectable in radio waves.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The finest precision for a magnetic field measurement was attained by Gravity Probe B at 5 aT (5×10−18 T).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The **H**-field cannot be directly measured but can be inferred from the currents that create it.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] sprinkled on paper placed above a bar magnet.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] needles point in the direction of the local magnetic field, towards a magnet's south pole and away from its north pole.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic field can be visualized by a set of *magnetic field lines*, that follow the direction of the field at each point.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The direction of the magnetic field at any point is parallel to the direction of nearby field lines, and the local density of field lines can be made proportional to its strength.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic field lines are like streamlines in fluid flow, in that they represent a continuous distribution, and a different resolution would show more or fewer lines.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] An advantage of using magnetic field lines as a representation is that many laws of magnetism (and electromagnetism) can be stated completely and concisely using simple concepts such as the "number" of field lines through a surface.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] These concepts can then be "translated" to their mathematical form.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For example, the number of field lines through a given surface is the surface integral of the magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This article uses almost entirely the SI unit system.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] But other unit systems, most importantly the Gaussian unit system (which is the most used system of cgs units for electromagnetism), are still being used in some disciplines, countries, and textbooks.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The equations for each unit system can be, and often are, different for different unit systems.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Moving electric charges including electrical currents experience a force due to magnetic **B** fields.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] A charged particle moving in a **B**-field experiences a *sideways* force that is proportional to the strength of the magnetic field, the component of the velocity that is perpendicular to the magnetic field and the charge of the particle.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where **F** is the force, *q* is the electric charge of the particle, **v** is the instantaneous velocity of the particle, and **B** is the magnetic field (in teslas).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The direction of force on the charge can be determined by the right-hand rule (see the figure).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The Lorentz force is always perpendicular to both the velocity of the particle and the magnetic field that created it.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] When a charged particle moves in a static magnetic field, it traces a helical path in which the helix axis is parallel to the magnetic field, and in which the speed of the particle remains constant.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] When a wire carrying a steady electric current is placed in an external magnetic field, each of the moving charges in the wire experience the Lorentz force.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Together, these forces produce a net macroscopic force on the wire.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This force (on a macroscopic current) is often referred to as the *Laplace force*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where I is the current and **ℓ** is a vector whose magnitude is the length of the wire, and whose direction is along the wire, aligned with the direction of the current.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] If the wire is not straight or the magnetic field is non-uniform, the total force can be computed by applying the formula to each infinitesimal segment of wire $\mathrm {d} {\boldsymbol {\ell }}$ , then adding up all these forces by integration.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This force creates an attractive/repulsive force between 2 parallel wires as the current through each produces a magnetic field that pushes/pulls on the other.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Too, a loop of current in a magnetic field will experience a torque due to the different direction of the force on different sides of the loop as describe in the next section.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] A magnetic field acting on a current carrying loop produces both a torque and a net force (if the magnetic field is non-uniform).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This effect is important for driving certain types of motors and in modeling forces and torques on atoms.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Calculating the torque on a rectangular loop is straightforward.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The diagram to the right shows a rectangular loop of current in a uniform magnetic **B** field (with a direction indicated by the green arrows).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For simplicity the loop is aligned so that it is along the direction of the magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic force on opposite sides of the loop are equal and opposite producing no net force on the loop.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The forces on the short sides (here shown as violet arrows), though, produce a net torque equal to the product of the force and the perpendicular distance between them.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Denoting the short side length as b, the magnitude of that force is F = IBb using the equation for the magnetic force on a straight wire given in the previous section.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The magnitude of the net torque (along dashed axis) is therefore N = IabB.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Here the direction of the area **A** is the normal to the area as determined by the right hand grip rule of the current loop.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] While derived for a rectangular loop this equation is valid for a flat loop of any shape and orientation.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] As described above, there is no net force on a loop in a uniform magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] However, non-uniform magnetic fields do produce a net force.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This net force tends to pull the object in direction of the stronger magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For a sufficiently small current loop, the details of the current loop such as it shape, area, orientation, and current around the loop are all hidden in **m** and otherwise do not matter.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] All magnetic dipoles with the same dipole moment **m** are affected the same way.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This force tends to push the magnetic dipole into the direction of increasing **B**.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] All moving charged particles produce magnetic fields.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Moving point charges, such as electrons, produce complicated but well known magnetic fields that depend on the charge, velocity, and acceleration of the particles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] These equations become much simpler when the moving charges form a steady state electrical current, the study of which is called magnetostatics.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In general, magnetic field lines form concentric circles around a current-carrying wire.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The direction of such a magnetic field can be determined by using the "right-hand grip rule" (see figure at right).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The strength of the magnetic field decreases with distance from the wire.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where *r* is the perpendicular distance to the wire.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The direction ${\hat {\phi }}$ of the magnetic field is tangent to a circle perpendicular to the wire according to the right hand rule.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Bending a current-carrying wire into a loop concentrates the magnetic field inside the loop while weakening it outside.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Bending a wire into multiple closely spaced loops to form a coil or 'solenoid' enhances this effect.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] A device so formed around an iron core may act as an electromagnet, generating a strong, well-controlled magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] An infinitely long solenoid has a uniform magnetic field inside, and no magnetic field outside.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where n is the number of turns per unit length of the solenoid and the direction of **H** is along the length of the solenoid.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] A finite length solenoid produces a more complicated magnetic field that can be evaluated mathematically.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For other examples of using the Biot-Savart law to calculate the magnetic fields for other common current configurations see #Common formulæ below.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where $\mathbf {m} =I\mathbf {A} =I(\pi a^{2}\mathbf {\hat {z}} )$ is the same magnetic dipole moment used in calculating the force and torque on a loop of current in #Net force and torque on a magnetic dipole above.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Calculating the on-axis magnetic fields of a square loop (and other flat geometries) yields similar equations that have the same equation at long distances as the circle: $\mathbf {H} ={\frac {\mathbf {m} }{2\pi z^{3}}}$ .
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Calculating the magnetic field at a arbitrary location **r** (not just on-axis) from an arbitrarily shaped current loop involves advanced math.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This equation shows that at sufficiently long distances the detailed geometry of a magnet can be replaced by a single quantity, the magnetic dipole moment **m**.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This equation, therefore makes a good model for the magnetic field of atoms and can be extended to describe magnetic material.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Too, it has some utility in calculating the long distance force between magnets.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where the line integral is over any arbitrary loop and $I_{\text{enc}}$ is the current enclosed by that loop.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The $I_{\text{enc}}$ is slightly different for the 2 equations in that **B** includes the difficult to calculate bound current in magnetic material while **H** does not.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Ampère's law is always valid for steady currents and can be used to easily calculate the magnetic fields of certain highly symmetric situations such as an infinite wire or an infinite solenoid.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In a modified form that accounts for time varying electric fields, Ampère's law is one of four Maxwell's equations that describe electricity and magnetism.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnets are objects that both create their own magnetic field and respond to the magnetic field of other magnets and magnetized materials.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The interaction between magnets and their interaction with magnetic field is extremely complicated.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The correct description involves describing each magnet as being made of many small volumes of magnetic material each of which creates its own magnetic field and responds to the magnetic field of the other volumes.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Such models are often extremely complex.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Fortunately, in many cases, it is sufficient to understand magnets as objects that have 2 equal but opposite magnetic poles: the magnetic north and south poles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Opposite poles attract with a force that increases with smaller distances while like poles repel in the same way.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Such a model is called a *magnetic pole model* and it, in some cases described below, can be used to make good quantitative predictions.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Specifying the force between magnets is quite complicated because it depends on the strength and orientation of both magnets and their distance and direction relative to each other.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The force is particularly sensitive to rotations of the magnets due to magnetic torque.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The force on each magnet depends on its magnetic moment and the magnetic field of the other.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For short distances (small r) the forces can be quite strong but it decreases quite rapidly (1/r4) for large distances.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For 2 sufficiently small magnets, such as 2 atoms far enough away from each other, the magnetic force can be represented as that of two infinitesimally small dipoles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where **r** is the distance-vector from dipole moment **m**1 to dipole moment **m**2, with *r* = ‖***r***‖.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The force acting on **m**1 is in the opposite direction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The net force depends on the orientation of both dipole moments relative to each other and relative to the distance-vector between them and it decreases rapidly (proportional to 1/r4).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For moderate distances it is often to sufficient model the force between magnets as the ***H**-field* of one magnet pushes and pulls on *both* poles of a second magnet.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] If this **H**-field is the same at both poles of the second magnet then there is no net force on that magnet since the force is opposite for opposite poles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] If, however, the magnetic field of the first magnet is *nonuniform* (such as the **H** near one of its poles), each pole of the second magnet sees a different field and is subject to a different force.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This difference in the two forces moves the magnet in the direction of increasing magnetic field and may also cause a net torque.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] If both poles are small enough to be represented as single points then they can be considered to be point magnetic charges.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where qm1 and qm2 are the **magnetic pole strengths** of each magnet (SI unit: ampere-meter), *μ* is the permeability of the intervening medium, and **r** is the separation distance between the 2 poles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Note that for 2 magnets (each having 2 poles) the sum of 4 forces is needed: each of the 2 poles of one magnet exerts a separate force on each of the 2 poles of the second magnet.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The pole description is useful to practicing magneticians who design real-world magnets, but real magnets have a pole distribution more complex than a single north and south.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Therefore, implementation of the pole idea is not simple.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In some cases, one of the more complex formulas given below will be more useful.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The mechanical force between two nearby magnetized surfaces can be calculated with the following equation.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where *A* is the surface area of the magnetic pole and μ0 is the permeability of free space.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This equation is also valid for the force of a magnetic pole on iron that is either almost touching or touching the magnetic pole.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] If two like poles of two separate magnets are brought near each other, and one of the magnets is allowed to turn, it promptly rotates to align itself with the first.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In this example, the magnetic field of the stationary magnet creates a *magnetic torque* on the magnet that is free to rotate.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This magnetic torque **N** tends to align a magnet's poles with the magnetic field lines.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] A compass, therefore, turns to align itself with Earth's magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] field induces the same torque on a current loop with the same magnetic dipole moment.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where × represents the vector cross product.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This equation includes all of the qualitative information included above.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] There is no torque on a magnet if **m** is in the same direction as the magnetic field, since the cross product is zero for two vectors that are in the same direction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Further, all other orientations feel a torque that twists them toward the direction of magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Most materials respond to an applied magnetic field by becoming magnetized (at least temporarily) which causes them to produce their own magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Typically, the response is weak and exists only when the magnetic field is applied.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] There are many different types of material that respond differently to the applied magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The term *magnet* is typically reserved for objects that produce their own persistent magnetic field even in the absence of an applied magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Only certain classes of materials can do this.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Most materials, however, produce a magnetic field in response to an applied magnetic field – a phenomenon known as magnetism.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] There are several types of magnetism, and all materials exhibit at least one of them.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The overall magnetic behavior of a material can vary widely, depending on the structure of the material, particularly on its electron configuration.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] It can also vary with temperature, pressure, and magnetic field strength such that a given material may have more than one magnetic phase.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In the case of paramagnetism and diamagnetism, the relationship between the applied magnetic field and the magnetization is often linear.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] However, superconductors and ferromagnets have a more complicated relation between the applied magnetic field and magnetization produced (see magnetic hysteresis).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] *Permanent magnets* are objects that produce their own persistent magnetic fields.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] They are made of ferromagnetic materials, such as iron and nickel, that have been magnetized.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic field of magnetized material is created at the atomic level.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The proper description of this effect involves quantum mechanics.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Fortunately, the net effect of adding up these magnetic interactions can often be calculated using much simpler models for the magnetic field created by the constituent atoms in the magnetic material.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This occurs because at large enough distance (or equivalently for small enough magnets) all the magnetic properties of any magnetic object can be described by a single (vector) quantity, the magnetic dipole moment, **m**.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] (See § Magnetic field of a flat loop of current (magnetic dipole) and § Net force and torque on a magnetic dipole above).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Objects that can be modeled this way, for example atoms, are called magnetic dipoles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic dipoles, therefore, are the building blocks of magnetization.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic field produced by magnetized material then is the net magnetic field of these dipoles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Too, the net force (and torque) on a magnetized material is a result of adding up the forces and torques on the individual dipoles that make up the magnetized material.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The *magnetization* vector field **M** represents how strongly a region of material is magnetized.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] It is defined as the net magnetic dipole moment per unit volume of that region.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetization of a uniformly magnetized magnet is therefore a constant, equal to the magnetic moment **m** of the magnet divided by its volume.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Since the SI unit of magnetic moment is A⋅m2, the SI unit of magnetization **M** is ampere per meter, identical to that of the **H**-field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetization **M** field of a region points in the direction of the average magnetic dipole moment in that region.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetization field lines, therefore, begin (inside the magnetized material) near the magnetic south pole and ends (inside the magnetized material) near the magnetic north pole.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In the Amperian loop model, the magnetization is due to combining many tiny magnetic dipole loops to form a resultant current called *bound current*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This bound current, then, is the source of the magnetic **B** field due to the magnet.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where the integral is a line integral over any closed loop and *I*b is the bound current enclosed by that closed loop.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Unlike the magnetic **B** field-lines which cannot begin nor end, magnetization field lines can begin and end.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Indeed they must begin and end where they intersects the boundary of the magnetized material (at magnetic poles) because the magnetization field only exists inside of a material.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This is analogous to electric field-lines which begin and end at electrical charges.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where the integral is a closed surface integral over the closed surface *S* and *q*M is the "magnetic charge" (in units of magnetic flux) enclosed by *S*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] (A closed surface completely surrounds a region with no holes to let any field lines escape.) The negative sign occurs because the magnetization field moves from south to north.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] No such magnetic charge exists; rather it is a convenient analogy that allows the use of much of the machinery developed for electrostatics with electric charge to be applied to magnetization with its fictitious magnetic charge.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For example the net magnetic charge of a pole is defined as a **magnetic pole strength** qm.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] From this equation, it is evident that outside of a magnetic material (where $\mathbf {M} =0$ ) that $\mathbf {B} =\mu _{0}\mathbf {H}$ .
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Outside a magnetic material, therefore, **B** and **H** are functionally identical just with different units since $\mu _{0}$ is a constant.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where If represents the 'free current' enclosed by the loop so that the line integral of **H** does not depend at all on the bound currents.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] which does not depend on the free currents.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The magnetic **H**-field, therefore, re-factors the bound current in terms of "magnetic charges".
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The **H** field lines loop only around "free current" and, unlike the magnetic **B** field, begins and ends near magnetic poles as well.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where *μ* is a material dependent parameter called the permeability.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In some cases the permeability may be a second rank tensor so that **H** may not point in the same direction as **B**.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] These relations between **B** and **H** are examples of constitutive equations.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In many real world applications such as small magnetic object inside of an extended applied magnetic field, the constitutive relation is not sufficient even if the material is linear.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This is because the **H**-field that the material experiences is not the same as the **H** applied.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In such cases, the magnetic field can still be calculated but care must be taken to distinguish the change of the magnetic field across the boundary of the magnetic object.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where the subscript t represents the tangential component of **H** and n represents its normal component.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For time varying magnetic fields (and more generally changing electrical currents or accelerating electrical charges), the magnetic and electric fields become linked such that a change in one induces the other.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Together, the electric and magnetic fields form an electromagnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The study of how the electric and magnetic fields interact in this way is called electrodynamics and includes many phenomenon that are important in physics and electrical engineering.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] It underlies transformers, and the generation and transmission of electrical power through wires and through space in the form of electromagnetic radiation of which light is one form.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Too, it allow magnetic fields to store and transmit energy.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] A time varying magnetic field through a loop of wire induces a current (more properly an EMF) through that loop.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This is known as electromagnetic induction and is important for many electronic devices such as inductors, transformers, and electrical generators.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] where ${\mathcal {E}}$ is the electromotive force (or *EMF*, the voltage generated around a closed loop) and Φ is the magnetic flux—the product of the area times the magnetic field normal to that area.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] (This definition of magnetic flux is why **B** is often referred to as *magnetic flux density*.) The negative sign represents the fact that any current generated by a changing magnetic field in a coil produces a magnetic field that *opposes* the *change* in the magnetic field that induced it.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Energy is needed to generate a magnetic field both to work against the electric field that a changing magnetic field creates and to change the magnetization of any material within the magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For non-dispersive materials, the energy used to magnetize the material is released when the magnetic field is destroyed so that the energy can be modeled as being stored in the magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The above equation cannot be used for nonlinear materials, though.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Once the relationship between **H** and **B** is known this equation is used to determine the work needed to reach a given magnetic state.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For hysteretic materials such as ferromagnets and superconductors, the work needed also depends on how the magnetic field is created.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] For linear non-dispersive materials, though, the general equation leads directly to the simpler energy density equation given above.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Magnetic field, together with the electric field, transmit electrical power.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Note that this power includes both the power transmitted by the electric and magnetic fields and the energy absorbed and emitted by magnetizing and polarizing the material.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Too, this equation only works for linear non-dispersive materials.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] This equations is also valid in a vacuum where **H** = **B**/μ0.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The time average of the poynting vector is known as irradiance and is an important quantity in optics that describes how intense light is at a given point.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] It is sometimes useful to calculate the magnetic field for a given set of time varying charges and currents, without having to use the complicated equations used to directly calculate it.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] An example of this is calculating the magnetic field of a light wave as it reflects and refracts at a surface.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In such cases Maxwell's equations are used to solve for both the magnetic and electric fields.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Maxwell's equations are a powerful set of differential equations that allows the calculation of the magnetic and electric fields for simple (and complex using computers and Finite Element Analysis) geometries.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Maxwell's Equations together with the Lorentz force law form a complete description of classical electrodynamics including both electricity and magnetism.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Maxwell's equations takes advantage of the fact that all vector fields (such as the electric and magnetic fields) can be expressed in terms of 2 types of *sources* and an appropriate set of boundary conditions.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The first type of *source* (an outflow source) causes the vector field to flow out (or in for a sink) to a given point.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The second (or circulation) source causes the vector field to rotate around a given point (forming vortices).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Both of these sources have well defined definitions and can be calculated from the vector field they create using a well-understood vector operator.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The divergence of a vector field **A**, **∇** · **A** is defined such that applying the divergence operator to a given vector field will yield the outflow sources.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The curl is defined such that **∇** × **A** yields the circulation source.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] An example of the power of these vector operators is: since it is an experimental fact that magnetic charges do not exist (and therefore there are no source nor sinks of **B**) the divergence of **B** must be zero, **∇** · **B** = 0, which is one of Maxwell's equations.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Maxwell's equation has 2 major versions: a microscopic version which necessitates knowing all of the charges and currents (including the complex ones at the atomic level) and the macroscopic version which depends only on the know 'free' charge and 'free' currents.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] Here the term 'free' means any charge or current that is directly controlled by the experiment and does not include the atomic level 'bound' charges and currents in a material which happen as a response to the electric and magnetic fields present in that material.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] In these equations, $\mathbf {D}$ is the electric displacement field, $\mathbf {E}$ the electric field, $\rho _{f}$ the free electric charge density, and $\mathbf {J} _{f}$ the free current density.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The first of Maxwell's equations is known as Gauss' Law but does not involve magnetic field so does not warrant further discussion here.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The second equation is Gauss' law for magnetism which reflects the non-existence of magnetic charge and allows **B** to be determined as the curl of a vector potential **A**.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] The third equation is Faraday's law of induction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p01] And, the fourth equation is Ampère's law with Maxwell's correction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In deriving advanced equations and in advanced topics such as quantum mechanics and relativity, it is often easier to work with a *potential formulation* of electrodynamics rather than in terms of the electric and magnetic fields.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The vector potential, ***A*** given by this form may be interpreted as a *generalized potential momentum per unit charge* just as *φ* is interpreted as a *generalized potential energy per unit charge*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] There are multiple choices one can make for the potential fields that satisfy the above condition.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] However, the choice of potentials is represented by its respective gauge condition.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Maxwell's equations when expressed in terms of the potentials can be cast into a form that explicitly agrees with special relativity.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Together, **A** and *φ* form the four-potential.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Using the four potential instead of electric and magnetic fields is much simpler—and it can be easily adapted to work with quantum mechanics.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic field is inherently a relativistic phenomena.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] More specifically, both electric and magnetic fields are the same phenomenon as seen in different reference frames: An electric force perceived by one observer may be perceived by another (in a different frame of reference) as a magnetic force, or a mixture of electric and magnetic forces.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] (Here different reference frames means one reference frame is moving relative to the other.) For relativistic phenomena, a lorentz transformation must be used to move (or transform) from one reference system to another.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] It is a straightforward task to show how the electric and magnetic fields transform from one reference frame to another.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The transformation rules, however are quite messy.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] One simple example is to examine how Coulomb's Law (which is a pure electric field of a charged particle in it own rest frame) transforms to a moving reference frame.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Formally, special relativity combines the electric and magnetic fields into a rank-2 tensor, called the *electromagnetic tensor*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Changing reference frames *mixes* these components.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] This is analogous to the way that special relativity *mixes* space and time into spacetime, and mass, momentum, and energy into four-momentum.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Similarly, the energy stored in a magnetic field is mixed with the energy stored in an electric field in the electromagnetic stress–energy tensor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The solution of maxwell's equations for electric and magnetic field of a point charge is expressed in terms of retarded time or the time at which the particle in the past causes the field at the point, given that the influence travels across space at the speed of light.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] where q is the charge of the point source, $n_{s}$ is a unit vector pointing from charged particle to the point in space, ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}_{s}(t)$ is the velocity of the particle divided by the speed of light and $\gamma (t)$ is the corresponding Lorentz factor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The classical electromagnetic field incorporated into quantum mechanics forms what is known as the semi-classical theory of radiation.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] However, it is not able to make experimentally observed predictions such as spontaneous emission process or Lamb shift implying the need for quantization of fields.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In modern physics, the electromagnetic field is understood to be not a *classical* field, but rather a quantum field; it is represented not as a vector of three numbers at each point, but as a vector of three quantum operators at each point.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The most accurate modern description of the electromagnetic interaction (and much else) is *quantum electrodynamics* (QED), which is incorporated into a more complete theory known as the *Standard Model of particle physics*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In QED, the magnitude of the electromagnetic interactions between charged particles (and their antiparticles) is computed using perturbation theory.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] These rather complex formulas produce a remarkable pictorial representation as Feynman diagrams in which virtual photons are exchanged.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Predictions of QED agree with experiments to an extremely high degree of accuracy: currently about 10−12 (and limited by experimental errors); for details see precision tests of QED.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] This makes QED one of the most accurate physical theories constructed thus far.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] All equations in this article are in the classical approximation, which is less accurate than the quantum description mentioned here.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] However, under most everyday circumstances, the difference between the two theories is negligible.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The Earth's magnetic field is produced by convection of a liquid iron alloy in the outer core.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In a dynamo process, the movements drive a feedback process in which electric currents create electric and magnetic fields that in turn act on the currents.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The field at the surface of the Earth is approximately the same as if a giant bar magnet were positioned at the center of the Earth and tilted at an angle of about 11° off the rotational axis of the Earth (see the figure).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The north pole of a magnetic compass needle points roughly north, toward the North Magnetic Pole.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] However, because a magnetic pole is attracted to its opposite, the North Magnetic Pole is actually the south pole of the geomagnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] This confusion in terminology arises because the pole of a magnet is defined by the geographical direction it points.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Earth's magnetic field is not constant—the strength of the field and the location of its poles vary.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Moreover, the poles periodically reverse their orientation in a process called geomagnetic reversal.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The most recent reversal occurred 780,000 years ago.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Measuring the Earths' magnetic field is a very useful tool in mineral exploration, oil exploration, and geological mapping.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] To cover large areas with uniform data, aircraft such as helicopters, airplanes, and drones are employed.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The amount of detail is a function of flight height and sample density, in addition to instrument sensitivity.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] For surveys, drones are used which helps greatly in the process.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Aeromagnetic surveys are also used to perform reconnaissance mapping of unexploded ordnance.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The *rotating magnetic field* is a common design principle in the operation of alternating-current motors.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] A permanent magnet in such a field rotates so as to maintain its alignment with the external field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic torque is used to drive electric motors.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In one simple motor design, a magnet is fixed to a freely rotating shaft and is subjected to a magnetic field from an array of electromagnets.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] By continuously switching the electric current through each of the electromagnets, thereby flipping the polarity of their magnetic fields, like poles are kept next to the rotor; the resultant torque is transferred to the shaft.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] A rotating magnetic field can be constructed using two coils at right angles with a phase difference of 90 degrees between their AC currents.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In practice, three-phase systems are used where the three currents are equal in magnitude and have a phase difference of 120 degrees.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Three similar coils at mutual geometrical angles of 120 degrees create the rotating magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The ability of the three-phase system to create a rotating field, utilized in electric motors, is one of the main reasons why three-phase systems dominate the world's electrical power supply systems.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Synchronous motors use DC-voltage-fed rotor windings, which lets the excitation of the machine be controlled—and induction motors use short-circuited rotors (instead of a magnet) following the rotating magnetic field of a multicoiled stator.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The short-circuited turns of the rotor develop eddy currents induced by the rotating field of the stator, and these currents in turn produce a torque on the rotor through the Lorentz force.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The Italian physicist Galileo Ferraris and the Serbian-American electrical engineer Nikola Tesla independently researched the use of rotating magnetic fields in electric motors.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In 1888, Ferraris published his research in a paper to the *Royal Academy of Sciences* in Turin and Tesla gained U.S. patent 381,968 for his work.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] An important use of **H** is in *magnetic circuits*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] A magnetic circuit is made up of one or more closed loop paths containing a magnetic flux.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The flux is usually generated by permanent magnets or electromagnets and confined to the path by magnetic cores consisting of ferromagnetic materials like iron, although there may be air gaps or other materials in the path.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic circuits are employed to efficiently channel magnetic fields in many devices such as electric motors, generators, transformers, relays, lifting electromagnets, SQUIDs, galvanometers, and magnetic recording heads.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The relation between the magnetic properties of a magnetic circuit can be described by Hopkinson's law, which bears a superficial resemblance to Ohm's law in electrical circuits, resulting in a one-to-one correspondence between properties of a magnetic circuit and an analogous electric circuit.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Using this concept the magnetic fields of complex devices such as transformers can be quickly solved using the methods and techniques developed for electrical circuits.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] where ${\textstyle \Phi =\int \mathbf {B} \cdot \mathrm {d} \mathbf {A} }$ is the magnetic flux in the circuit, ${\textstyle F=\int \mathbf {H} \cdot \mathrm {d} {\boldsymbol {\ell }}}$ is the magnetomotive force applied to the circuit, and *R*m is the magnetic reluctance of the circuit.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Here the reluctance *R*m is a quantity similar in nature to resistance for the flux.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Using this analogy it is straightforward to calculate the magnetic flux of complicated magnetic field geometries, by using all the available techniques of circuit theory.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic levitation is used for maglev trains, contactless melting, magnetic bearings, and for product display purposes.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetic field affects materials in a large number of ways.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The charge carriers of a current-carrying conductor placed in a transverse magnetic field experience a sideways Lorentz force; this results in a charge separation in a direction perpendicular to the current and to the magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The resultant voltage in that direction is proportional to the applied magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The *Hall effect* is often used to measure the magnitude of a magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] It is used as well to find the sign of the dominant charge carriers in materials such as semiconductors (negative electrons or positive holes).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The largest magnitude magnetic field produced over a macroscopic volume outside a lab setting is 2.8 kT (VNIIEF in Sarov, Russia, 1998).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The largest magnitude magnetic field produced in a laboratory over a macroscopic volume was 1.2 kT by researchers at the University of Tokyo in 2018.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The largest magnitude microscopic magnetic fields produced in a laboratory occur in particle accelerators, such as RHIC, inside the collisions of heavy ions, where microscopic fields reach 1014 T.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Magnetars have the strongest known macroscopic magnetic fields of any naturally occurring object, ranging from 0.1 to 100 GT (108 to 1011 T).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] While magnets and some properties of magnetism were known to ancient societies, the research of magnetic fields began in 1269 when French scholar Petrus Peregrinus de Maricourt mapped out the magnetic field on the surface of a spherical magnet using iron needles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Noting the resulting field lines crossed at two points he named those points "poles" in analogy to Earth's poles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] He also articulated the principle that magnets always have both a north and south pole, no matter how finely one slices them.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In 1600 (almost three centuries later), William Gilbert of Colchester published *De Magnete*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In *De Magnete*, Gilbert replicated Petrus Peregrinus' work and was the first to state explicitly that Earth is a magnet.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Too, he argued that electricity and magnetism were separate phenomenon.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In 1750, John Michell stated that magnetic poles attract and repel in accordance with an inverse square law Charles-Augustin de Coulomb experimentally verified this in 1785 and stated explicitly that north and south poles cannot be separated.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Building on this force between poles, Siméon Denis Poisson (1781–1840) created the first successful model of the magnetic field, which he presented in 1824.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Three discoveries in 1820 challenged this foundation of magnetism.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Hans Christian Ørsted demonstrated that a current-carrying wire is surrounded by a circular magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Then André-Marie Ampère showed that parallel wires with currents attract one another if the currents are in the same direction and repel if they are in opposite directions.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Finally, Jean-Baptiste Biot and Félix Savart announced empirical results about the forces that a current-carrying long, straight wire exerted on a small magnet, determining the forces were inversely proportional to the perpendicular distance from the wire to the magnet.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Laplace later deduced a law of force based on the differential action of a differential section of the wire, which became known as the Biot–Savart law, as Laplace did not publish his findings.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Extending these experiments, Ampère published his own successful model of magnetism in 1825.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In it, he showed the equivalence of electrical currents to magnets and proposed that magnetism is due to perpetually flowing loops of current instead of the dipoles of magnetic charge in Poisson's model.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Further, Ampère derived both Ampère's force law describing the force between two currents and Ampère's law, which, like the Biot–Savart law, correctly described the magnetic field generated by a steady current.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Also in his 1825 work, Ampère introduced the term electrodynamics to describe the relationship between electricity and magnetism.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In 1831, Michael Faraday discovered electromagnetic induction when he found that a changing magnetic field generates an encircling electric field, formulating what is now known as Faraday's law of induction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Later, Franz Ernst Neumann proved that, for a moving conductor in a magnetic field, induction is a consequence of Ampère's force law.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In the process, he introduced the magnetic vector potential, which was later shown to be equivalent to the underlying mechanism proposed by Faraday.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In 1850, Lord Kelvin, then known as William Thomson, distinguished between two magnetic fields now denoted **H** and **B**.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The former applied to Poisson's model and the latter to Ampère's model and induction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Further, he derived how **H** and **B** relate to each other and coined the term *permeability*.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Between 1861 and 1865, James Clerk Maxwell developed and published Maxwell's equations, which explained and united all of classical electricity and magnetism.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The first set of these equations was published in a paper entitled *On Physical Lines of Force* in 1861.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] These equations were valid but incomplete.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Maxwell completed his set of equations in his later 1865 paper *A Dynamical Theory of the Electromagnetic Field* and demonstrated the fact that light is an electromagnetic wave.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Heinrich Hertz published papers in 1887 and 1888 experimentally confirming this fact.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In 1887, Tesla developed an induction motor that ran on alternating current.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The motor used polyphase current, which generated a rotating magnetic field to turn the motor (a principle that Tesla claimed to have conceived in 1882).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Tesla received a patent for his electric motor in May 1888.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] In 1885, Galileo Ferraris independently researched rotating magnetic fields and subsequently published his research in a paper to the *Royal Academy of Sciences* in Turin, just two months before Tesla was awarded his patent, in March 1888.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] The twentieth century showed that classical electrodynamics is already consistent with special relativity, and extended classical electrodynamics to work with quantum mechanics.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Albert Einstein, in his paper of 1905 that established relativity, showed that both the electric and magnetic fields are part of the same phenomena viewed from different reference frames.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] Finally, the emergent field of quantum mechanics was merged with electrodynamics to form quantum electrodynamics (or QED).
[src:hall-effect-sensors/magnetic-field-p02] QED mathematically describes all phenomena involving electrically charged particles interacting by means of exchange of photons and represents the quantum counterpart of classical electromagnetism giving a complete account of matter and light interaction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The **reed switch** is an electromechanical switch operated by an applied magnetic field.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] It was invented in 1922 by professor Valentin Kovalenkov at the Petrograd Electrotechnical University, and later evolved at Bell Telephone Laboratories in 1936 by Walter B.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] In its simplest and most common form, it consists of a pair of ferromagnetic flexible metal contacts in a hermetically sealed glass envelope.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The contacts are usually normally open, closing when a magnetic field is present, or they may be normally closed and open when a magnetic field is applied.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The switch may be actuated by an electromagnetic coil, making a reed relay, or by bringing a permanent magnet near it.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] When the magnetic field is removed, the contacts in the reed switch return to their original position.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The "reed" is the metal part inside the reed switch envelope that is relatively thin and wide to make it flexible, resembling the reed of a musical instrument.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The term "reed" may also include the external wire lead as well as the internal part.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] A common example of a reed switch application is to detect the opening of a door or windows, for a security alarm.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The most common type of reed switch contains a pair of magnetizable, flexible, metal reeds whose end portions are separated by a small gap when the switch is open.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The reeds are hermetically sealed within a tubular glass envelope.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Another type of reed switch contains one flexible reed that moves between a fixed normally-open contact and a fixed normally-closed contact.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The normally-closed contact is non-ferromagnetic and is closed by the flexible reed's spring force.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Although reed switches with multiple poles are possible, more often an assembly of single-pole reed switches is used for multi-pole applications.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] A magnetic field from an electromagnet or a permanent magnet will cause the reeds to attract each other, thus completing an electrical circuit.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The spring force of the reeds causes them to separate, and open the circuit, when the magnetic field ceases.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Another configuration contains a non-ferromagnetic normally-closed contact that opens when the ferromagnetic normally-open contact closes.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switch contacts are typically rhodium, ruthenium, iridium, or tungsten.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] There are also versions of reed switches with mercury-wetted contacts.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Such switches must be mounted in a particular orientation, lest drops of mercury bridge the contacts even when not activated.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Since the contacts of the reed switch are sealed away from the atmosphere, they are protected against atmospheric corrosion.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The hermetic sealing of a reed switch make them suitable for use in explosive atmospheres where tiny sparks from conventional switches would constitute a hazard.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] One important quality of the switch is its sensitivity, the amount of magnetic field necessary to actuate it.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Sensitivity is measured in units of ampere-turns (AT), corresponding to the current in a test coil multiplied by the number of turns in the test coil.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Typical pull-in sensitivities for commercial devices are in the 10 to 60 AT range.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The lower the AT, the more sensitive the reed switch.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Smaller reed switches, which have smaller parts, are generally more sensitive to magnetic fields.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] In production, a metal reed is inserted in each end of a glass tube and the ends of the tube are heated so that they seal around a shank portion on the reeds.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Green-colored infrared-absorbing glass is frequently used, so an infrared heat source can concentrate the heat in the small sealing zone of the glass tube.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The thermal coefficient of expansion of the glass material and metal parts must be similar to prevent breaking the glass-to-metal seal.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The glass used must have a high electrical resistance and must not contain volatile components, such as lead oxide and fluorides, which can contaminate the contacts during the sealing operation.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The leads of the switch must be handled carefully to prevent breaking the glass envelope.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The glass envelope can be damaged if the reed switch is subjected to mechanical stress.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Most reed switches are filled with nitrogen at atmospheric pressure.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] After the final seal is made, the switch cools and the internal pressure is less than one atmosphere.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches sealed with a pressurized nitrogen atmosphere have a higher breakdown voltage and are useful for switching 220–240 VAC mains power.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches with a vacuum inside the glass envelope can switch thousands of volts.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches can be used to directly switch a variety of loads ranging from nanovolts to kilovolts, femtoamperes to amperes, and DC to radio frequency.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Other magnetically-activated switching devices have a limited range of output voltages and currents, and generally do not directly control a final device such as a lamp, solenoid, or motor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches have small leakage currents compared to solid state devices; this may be useful, for example, in medical devices requiring protection of a patient from tiny leakage currents.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The reed is hermetically sealed and can therefore operate in almost any environment, such as where flammable gas is present or where corrosion would affect open switch contacts.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] A reed switch has very low resistance when closed, typically as low as 0.05 ohms, whereas the Hall effect sensors can be in the hundreds of ohms.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] A reed switch requires only two wires whereas most solid-state devices require three wires.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] A reed switch can be said to require zero power to operate it.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] One or more reed switches inside an electromagnetic coil constitute a reed relay.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed relays are used when operating currents are relatively low, and offer high operating speed, good performance with very small currents that are not reliably switched by conventional contacts, high reliability and long life.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Millions of reed relays were used in telephone exchanges in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] In particular, they were used for switching in the British TXE family of telephone exchanges.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The inert atmosphere around the reed contacts ensures that oxidation will not affect the contact resistance.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Mercury-wetted reed relays are sometimes used, especially in high-speed counting circuits.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches actuated by magnets are commonly used in mechanical systems as proximity sensors.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Examples are door and window sensors in burglar alarm systems and tamperproofing methods.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches have been used in laptops to put the laptop into sleep/hibernation mode when the lid is closed.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Speed sensors on bicycle wheels frequently use a reed switch to actuate briefly each time a magnet on the wheel passes the sensor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] At one time brushless DC electric motors used reed switches to sense the rotor's position relative to the field poles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] This allowed switching transistors to act as a commutator, but without the contact problems, wear and electrical noise of a traditional DC commutator.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The motor design could also be "inverted", placing permanent magnets onto the rotor and switching the field through the external, fixed coils.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] This avoided the need for any rubbing contact to provide power to the rotor.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Such motors were used in low-power long-service-life items, such as computer cooling fans and disk drives.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] As cheap Hall effect sensors became available, they replaced the reed switches and gave even longer service lifetimes.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches are used in at least one brand of endoscopic capsule to switch on the power source only when the unit is removed from the sterile packaging.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches may be selected for a particular sensor application when a solid-state device does not meet requirements such as power consumption or electrical interface compatibility.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches were formerly used in the keyboards for computer terminals, where each key had a magnet and a reed switch actuated by depressing the key.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Reed switches in keyboards have largely been superseded by Hall effect switches.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Electric and electronic pedal keyboards used by pipe organ and Hammond organ players often use reed switches, where the glass enclosure of the contacts protects them from dirt, dust, and other particles.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] They may also be used to control diving equipment, such as flashlights or cameras, which must be sealed to keep water out under high pressure.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] The mechanical motion of the reeds is below the fatigue limit of the materials, so the reeds do not break due to fatigue.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Wear and life are almost entirely dependent on the electrical circuit's effect on the contacts along with the properties of the specific reed switch used.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Contact surface wear occurs only when the switch contacts open or close.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Because of this, manufacturers rate life in number of operations rather than hours or years.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] In general, higher voltages and higher currents cause faster wear and shorter life.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/reed-switch] Depending on the electrical load, life can be in the range of thousands of operations or billions of operations.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The **Wiegand effect** is a nonlinear magnetic effect, named after its discoverer John R.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Wiegand, produced in specially annealed and hardened wire called Wiegand wire.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Wiegand wire is low-carbon Vicalloy, a ferromagnetic alloy of cobalt, iron, and vanadium.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] In this state the alloy is "soft" in the magnetic sense; that is, it is attracted to magnets and so magnetic field lines will divert preferentially into the metal, but the metal retains only a very small residual field when the external field is removed.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] During manufacture, to give the wire its unique magnetic properties, it is subjected to a series of twisting and untwisting operations to cold-work the outside shell of the wire while retaining a soft core within the wire, and then the wire is aged.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The result is that the magnetic coercivity of the outside shell is much larger than that of the inner core.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] This high coercivity outer shell will retain an external magnetic field even when the field's original source is removed.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] This switchover occurs in a few microseconds, and is called the Wiegand effect.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The value of the Wiegand effect is that the switchover speed is sufficiently fast that a significant voltage can be output from a coil using a Wiegand-wire core.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Because the voltage induced by a changing magnetic field is proportional to the rate of change of the field, a Wiegand-wire core can increase the output voltage of a magnetic field sensor by several orders of magnitude as compared to a similar coil with a non-Wiegand core.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] This higher voltage can easily be detected electronically, and when combined with the high repeatability threshold of the magnetic field switching, making the Wiegand effect useful for positional sensors.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Once the Wiegand wire has flipped magnetization, it will retain that magnetization until flipped in the other direction.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Sensors and mechanisms that use the Wiegand effect must take this retention into account.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The Wiegand effect is a macroscopic extension of the Barkhausen effect, as the special treatment of the Wiegand wire causes the wire to act macroscopically as a single large magnetic domain.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The numerous small high-coercivity domains in the Wiegand wire outer shell switch in an avalanche, generating the Wiegand effect's rapid magnetic field change.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Wiegand sensors are magnetic sensors that make use of the Wiegand effect to generate a consistent pulse every time magnetic field polarity reverses and therefore do not rely on any external voltage or current.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The consistency of the pulses produced by Wiegand sensors can be used to provide energy for low-power and energy-saving applications.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Being self-powered, Wiegand sensors have a potential in IoT applications as energy harvesters, proximity sensors, and event counters.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Wiegand and Milton Velinsky developed an access control card using Wiegand wires.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Besides sensors, the Wiegand effect is used for security keycard door locks.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The plastic keycard has a series of short lengths of Wiegand wire embedded in it, which encodes the key by the presence or absence of wires.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] A second track of wires provides a clock track.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The card is read by pulling it through a slot in a reader device, which has a fixed magnetic field and a sensor coil.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] As each length of wire passes through the magnetic field, its magnetic state flips, which indicates a 1, and this is sensed by the coil.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The resulting Wiegand protocol digital code is then sent to a host controller to determine whether to electrically unlock the door.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Wiegand cards are more durable and difficult to counterfeit than bar code or magnetic stripe cards.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Since the keycode is permanently set into the card at manufacture by the positions of the wires, Wiegand cards can't be erased by magnetic fields or reprogrammed as magnetic stripe cards can.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] The Wiegand interface, originally developed for Wiegand-wire cards, is still the de-facto standard convention for transmitting data from any kind of access card to an access control panel.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] A capacitive MM code card, like Wiegand cards, embeds a code inside the plastic of the card, and so are more durable and difficult to counterfeit than magnetic stripes or printed barcodes on the surface of the card.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Wiegand wires are used by some rotary magnetic encoders to power the multi-turn circuitry.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] As the encoder revolves, the Wiegand wire core coil generates a pulse of electricity sufficient to power the encoder and write the turns count to non-volatile memory.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] This works at any speed of rotation and eliminates the clock/gear mechanism typically associated with multi-turn encoders.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] Wiegand wires are fitted to the outer diameter of a wheel to measure rotational speeds.
[src:hall-effect-sensors/wiegand-effect] An externally mounted reading head detects the Wiegand pulses.
